messages.content: What is the purpose of the LCM_Inpaint-Outpaint_Comfy custom nodes?
Custom nodes in ComfyUI allow inpainting and outpainting images using a latent consistency model (LCM).
Where should I place the model folders for the ControlNet/T2I Adapter and IP Adapter nodes?
Place the ControlNet/T2I Adapter model folders inside 'ComfyUI/models/controlnet'. And place the IP Adapter model folders inside 'ComfyUI/models/controlnet'.
How do I use the LCM_Inpaint-Outpaint_Comfy nodes?

Clone the custom_nodes folder inside your ComfyUI directory.
Install the required libraries.
Download the LCM_Dreamshaper_v7 model and place it inside the 'model/diffusers' folder. Load the workflow by choosing the '.json' file for inpainting or outpainting.
Why might there be errors on Windows when using LCM_Inpaint-Outpaint_Comfy custom nodes?
The paths in the nodes might be formatted for Linux and not Windows.
How can I control the strength of the effects of the inpainting and outpainting models?
Use the '+' and '-' symbols to adjust the effect of the models. More '+' or '-' increases or decreases the effects.
What is the purpose of the 'FreeU' node?
The 'FreeU' node is not explicitly described in the provided text.
Where can I find further information about the LCM_Inpaint-Outpaint_Comfy custom nodes?
The GitHub repository for LCM_Inpaint-Outpaint_Comfy provides documentation and resources.
